# Backlog grooming with PM + tech lead (weekly)

## Context

1-hour weekly session: PM brings business priorities, tech lead brings tech-debt + capacity reality. Output: top-of-backlog is spec-ready (acceptance criteria + estimated complexity), nothing else. AI agent splits oversized items into sub-tasks.

## Outcome

By the end of this playbook, the operator has run the 3 stages below and produced the written decision artefact in the final stage.

Success criteria:

- All 3 stages have written outputs in the project record
- Each stage's decision gate was answered before advancing (yes / no in writing)
- Final stage produced the required written decision artifact
- Every methodology reference loaded cleanly via `faion get-content`

## Steps

### 1. Pre-Read

PM + tech lead both prep before meeting.

Tasks:
- PM brings the candidate items with outcomes + value notes
- Tech lead reads the candidates and flags feasibility risks
- Both pre-agree the top 5 items to discuss

Outputs:
- candidate list with value
- feasibility notes
- top-5 agenda

Decision gate: Advance only when both arrive with the pre-read done.

### 2. Groom Live

Time-boxed; no rambling.

Tasks:
- Walk top 5; either ready / needs-info / drop
- Write acceptance criteria for ready items
- Estimate complexity (S/M/L) — not time

Outputs:
- per-item ready/needs/drop
- acceptance criteria for ready items
- complexity tags

Decision gate: Advance when every top-5 item has a ready/needs/drop verdict.

### 3. Update & Communicate

Make the meeting count.

Tasks:
- Update the backlog with the changes from the meeting
- Post the grooming summary to the team channel
- Calendar any needs-info follow-ups

Outputs:
- updated backlog
- grooming summary post
- follow-up calendar entries

Decision gate: Required output: a published grooming summary.

## Decision points

- Stage 1 (Pre-Read): Advance only when both arrive with the pre-read done.
- Stage 2 (Groom Live): Advance when every top-5 item has a ready/needs/drop verdict.
- Stage 3 (Update & Communicate): Required output: a published grooming summary.

